{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/lies-damn-lies-and-data-visualisation-39e20991e7da", "time": 1682996616.787084, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/lies-damn-lies-and-data-visualisation-39e20991e7da/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Lies, Damn Lies, and Data Visualisation | by Callum Ballard | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Lies, Damn Lies, and Data Visualisation", "description": "As an analyst or data scientist, it might feel like creating insight from a million-row dataframe is the hard part of the process. You spend hours scrubbing null-values, transforming data, testing\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/How_to_Lie_with_Statistics", "anchor_text": "\u2018How To Lie With Statistics\u2019", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternative_facts", "anchor_text": "Sean Spicer\u2019s alternative facts", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://www.theguardian.com/politics/reality-check/2016/may/23/does-the-eu-really-cost-the-uk-350m-a-week", "anchor_text": "dodgy claims on the side of a 2016 campaign bus", "paragraph_index": 11}], "all_paragraphs": ["As an analyst or data scientist, it might feel like creating insight from a million-row dataframe is the hard part of the process.", "You spend hours scrubbing null-values, transforming data, testing hypotheses, recording R\u00b2s, and scrutinising p-values. At some point, you reach a conclusion. You sit back, smug in the knowledge that you\u2019ve discovered some truly groundbreaking insight.", "And now you need to tell the world all about it.", "If mathematics, data science, and statistics are dialects of a single foreign language, then data visualisation might be thought of as a Rosetta Stone, allowing number crunchers to convey insight to kind of person who might, quite reasonably, assume that \u2018y-hat\u2019 is a question about headwear.", "Thinking about how to show insight is, in and of itself, a fine art. If one doesn\u2019t visualise data appropriately, then, frankly, it will not be understood. And this is true regardless of who the insight is being shared with. In my previous life as a management consultant, I saw perfectly sound, evidence-driven recommendations dismissed by clients \u2014 even CEOs \u2014 due to bad presentation of that evidence. And one could hardly accuse a CEO of innumeracy, or of generally ignoring sound advice.", "I also know from bitter personal experience that a bafflingly formatted chart can even confuse a colleague who\u2019s worked on the same dataset that the very insight was derived from. Thus, whenever I was training new recruits on this matter, I\u2019d encourage them to follow a short list of simple data visualisation rules:", "The key to achieving the above (give or take the last point) is effective use of Preattentive Attributes \u2014 the fundamental visual properties of any graphic.", "Preattentive processing, i.e. the act of extracting \u2018obvious\u2019 visual information, as in the above examples, takes place in sensory memory. It requires no conscious effort from the viewer, and it takes less than 500 milliseconds to complete. Effective data visualisation, then, is not just about allowing a viewer to read numbers off an axis, it\u2019s about appealing to their very subconscious.", "\u201cStatistical thinking will one day be as necessary for efficient citizenship as the ability to read and write.\u201d \u2014 H.G. Wells", "Of course, a reputable data scientist should go out of their way to ensure that visualisations don\u2019t misrepresent the data. They should also present their findings in such a way that a reader is able to take unambiguous, accurate messages from them.", "However, if the numbers don\u2019t back up the kind of messages you were hoping for, then data could be still presented in such a way that told the desired story. Even before the world took on its recent post-truth bent, statistics, and the visualisation thereof, were often deployed with this kind of ulterior motive.", "The best-selling book, \u2018How To Lie With Statistics\u2019 by Darrell Huff, was not written in response to Sean Spicer\u2019s alternative facts, or dodgy claims on the side of a 2016 campaign bus. It was in fact published in 1954, though many of the themes within it will be familiar to a modern audience (chapter titles include \u2018The Sample With Built-in Bias\u2019, \u2018The Well-Chosen Average\u2019, and \u2018The Gee-Wizz Graph).", "Some modern examples of data visualisation, so obviously designed in order to deceive the viewer, appear almost comical when placed under even the most cursory of scrutiny. But even if the numbers are literally written on the charts, the first visual impression (often informed by a mutilated y-axis) counts for a lot. The graphs\u2019 Preattentive Attributes shine through, demanding the viewer\u2019s attention. And a person\u2019s subconscious, fine tuned by a million years of evolution, is a hard thing to argue with.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Analysis Lead at Cleo AI, McKinsey & LSE Alumni, previously published in The Economist. Typically found listening to Japanese Math Rock..."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F39e20991e7da&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Flies-damn-lies-and-data-visualisation-39e20991e7da&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Flies-damn-lies-and-data-visualisation-39e20991e7da&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------g